{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17628652","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17628652"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T17:00:10+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T17:00:10+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17232"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17232","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17232"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9922"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"69498"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9922","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9922"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17232"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"54950"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"4937"},{"type":"tags","id":"4940"},{"type":"tags","id":"4945"},{"type":"tags","id":"7615"},{"type":"tags","id":"7620"},{"type":"tags","id":"7662"},{"type":"tags","id":"10748"},{"type":"tags","id":"10752"},{"type":"tags","id":"10773"},{"type":"tags","id":"10774"},{"type":"tags","id":"11066"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"23268"},{"type":"contributions","id":"23271"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"69498","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/69498"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EEpigenetic modifications play a crucial role in cancer development. These changes can alter gene expression without changing the DNA sequence itself.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes DNA methylation patterns typically observed in cancer cells?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Global hypermethylation with local hypomethylation of oncogenes","Complete loss of all DNA methylation","Equal distribution of methylation across all genes","Increased methylation of all gene promoters","Global hypomethylation with local hypermethylation of tumor suppressor genes"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003ECancer cells typically show \u003Cstrong\u003Eglobal hypomethylation with local hypermethylation of tumor suppressor genes\u003C/strong\u003E. This pattern contributes to genomic instability and inappropriate gene silencing, promoting cancer development.\u003C/p\u003E        \u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E        \u003Cul\u003E        \u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGlobal hypermethylation with local hypomethylation of oncogenes\u003C/strong\u003E - This is the opposite of what occurs in cancer cells\u003C/li\u003E                \u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEqual distribution of methylation across all genes\u003C/strong\u003E - Cancer cells show distinct patterns of altered methylation rather than equal distribution\u003C/li\u003E                \u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EComplete loss of all DNA methylation\u003C/strong\u003E - While global hypomethylation occurs, some regions become hypermethylated\u003C/li\u003E                \u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIncreased methylation of all gene promoters\u003C/strong\u003E - Only specific promoters, particularly those of tumor suppressor genes, show increased methylation\u003C/li\u003E    \u003C/ul\u003E        \u003Cp\u003EGlobal hypomethylation can activate oncogenes and cause chromosomal instability, while local hypermethylation silences tumor suppressor genes. Both changes contribute to cancer development and progression.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["DNA methylation typically occurs at CpG islands and is associated with gene silencing.","Cancer cells often show global DNA hypomethylation but local hypermethylation at tumor suppressor genes.","Epigenetic changes in cancer are potentially reversible, unlike genetic mutations."],"references":["Turnpenny PD, Ellard S. Emery\u0027s Elements of Medical Genetics E-Book: Elsevier Health Sciences; 2011","Yu X, Zhao H, Wang R, Chen Y, Ouyang X, Li W, et al. Cancer epigenetics: from laboratory studies and clinical trials to precision medicine. Cell Death Discovery. 2024;10(1):28. Available at: https://www.nature.com/articles/s41420-024-01803-z"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"54950"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17232"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"54950","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/54950"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-12T10:06:18+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-12T10:10:15+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9922"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"69498"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"76","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/76"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level II","synonyms":null,"description":"Understand (interpreting and summarizing information)"